# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cheminformatics-rdkit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] A **chemical file format** is a type of data file which is used specifically for depicting molecular data.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] One of the most widely used is the chemical table file format, which is similar to *Structure Data Format* (SDF) files.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] They are text files that represent multiple chemical structure records and associated data fields.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The XYZ file format is a simple format that usually gives the number of atoms in the first line, a comment on the second, followed by a number of lines with atomic symbols (or atomic numbers) and cartesian coordinates.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The Protein Data Bank Format is commonly used for proteins but is also used for other types of molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] There are many other types which are detailed below.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Various software systems are available to convert from one format to another.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Chemical information is usually provided as files or streams and many formats have been created, with varying degrees of documentation.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Chemical Markup Language (CML) is an open standard for representing molecular and other chemical data.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The open source project includes XML Schema, source code for parsing and working with CML data, and an active community.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The articles Tools for Working with Chemical Markup Language and XML for Chemistry and Biosciences discusses CML in more detail.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] CML data files are accepted by many tools, including JChemPaint, Jmol, XDrawChem and MarvinView.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Simpler chemical format focus on describing the connectivity of atoms (and sometimes their stereochemistry).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] InChI is an IUPAC-standard format for describing molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Multiple InChI strings can be joined into an "RInChI" to describe a chemical reaction, or into a "MInChI" to describe a mixture.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The simplified molecular input line entry system, or SMILES, is a line notation for molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] SMILES strings include connectivity but do not include 2D or 3D coordinates.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Other atoms are represented by their element symbols `B`, `C`, `N`, `O`, `F`, `P`, `S`, `Cl`, `Br`, and `I`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The symbol `=` represents double bonds and `#` represents triple bonds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Multiple SMILES strings can be joined into a "reaction SMILES", which describes a chemical reaction.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] SYBYL Line Notation (SLN) is a chemical line notation.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Based on SMILES, it incorporates a complete syntax for specifying relative stereochemistry.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] SLN has a rich query syntax that allows for the specification of Markush structure queries.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The syntax also supports the specification of combinatorial libraries of ChemDraw.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Some chemical formats describe the coordinates of atoms.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] One of the most widely used industry standards are the chemical table file formats.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] They are text files that adhere to a strict format for representing multiple chemical structure records and associated data fields.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The format was originally developed and published by Molecular Design Limited (MDL).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] This family includes the MOLfile, the SDfile (Structure Data Format, MOLfile with metadata), the RXNfile (multiple MOLfiles put together to describe a chemical reaction), and RDfile (RXNfile with metadata).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The Protein Data Bank Format is an obsolete format for protein structures developed in 1972.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] It is a fixed-width format and thus limited to a maximum number of atoms, residues, and chains; this resulted in splitting very large structures such as ribosomes into multiple files.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] For example, the E. coli 70S was represented as 4 PDB files in 2009: 3I1M Archived 2016-10-05 at the Wayback Machine, 3I1N Archived 2016-10-16 at the Wayback Machine, 3I1O, and 3I1P.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] In 2014, they were consolidated into a single file, 4V6C.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Some PDB files contained an optional section describing atom connectivity as well as position.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Because these files were sometimes used to describe macromolecular assemblies or molecules represented in explicit solvent, they could grow very large and were often compressed.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Some tools, such as Jmol and KiNG, could read PDB files in gzipped format.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The wwPDB maintained the specifications of the PDB file format and its XML alternative, PDBML.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] There was a fairly major change in PDB format specification (to version 3.0) in August 2007, and a remediation of many file problems in the existing database.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The typical file extension for a PDB file was *`.pdb`*, although some older files used *`.ent`* or *`.brk`*.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Some molecular modeling tools wrote nonstandard PDB-style files that adapted the basic format to their own needs.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The GROMACS file format family was created for use with the molecular simulation software package GROMACS.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] It closely resembles the PDB format but was designed for storing output from molecular dynamics simulations, so it allows for additional numerical precision and optionally retains information about particle velocity as well as position at a given point in the simulation trajectory.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] It does not allow for the storage of connectivity information, which in GROMACS is obtained from separate molecule and system topology files.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The typical file extension for a GROMACS file is *`.gro`*.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The CHARMM molecular dynamics package can read and write a number of standard chemical and biochemical file formats; however, the CARD (coordinate) and PSF (protein structure file) are largely unique to CHARMM.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The CARD format is fixed-column-width, resembles the PDB format, and is used exclusively for storing atomic coordinates.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The PSF file contains atomic connectivity information (which describes atomic bonds) and is required before beginning a simulation.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The typical file extensions used are *`.crd`* and *`.psf`* respectively.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] In 2014, the PDB format was officially replaced with mmCIF. mmCIF is a new text format for representing atomic coordinates and "biological assemblies", i.e. assemblies of molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] It can express things that the PDB format cannot express, so some newer PDB structures may not have PDB files available (but a "bundle file" containing PDB files split from the main mmCIF file can be downloaded).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] There is also a more verbose XML variant.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The General Simulation Data (GSD) file format created for efficient reading / writing of generic particle simulations, primarily - but not restricted to - those from HOOMD-blue.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The Ghemical software can use OpenBabel to import and export a number of file formats.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] However, by default, it uses the GPR format.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] This file is composed of several parts, separated by a tag (`!Header`, `!Info`, `!Atoms`, `!Bonds`, `!Coord`, `!PartialCharges` and `!End`).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] PubChem offers data export for SDF, JSON, XML, and ASNT/B formats.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] These "formats" are references to entries in specific databases.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The Mixfile format is a JSON-based format for describing mixtures.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Just like extension names are used to distinguish file types in folders, MIME types are used to distinguish data-stream types on the Internet.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] "Chemical MIME" is a project for proposing MIME types to chemical streams.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] In 1998 the work was formally published in the JCIM.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] For Linux/Unix, configuration files are available as a "*chemical-mime-data*" package in .deb, RPM and tar.gz formats to register chemical MIME types on a web server.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Programs can then register as viewer, editor or processor for these formats so that full support for chemical MIME types is available.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] OpenBabel and JOELib are freely available open source tools specifically designed for converting between file formats.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Their chemical expert systems support a large atom type conversion tables.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] IOData is a free and open-source Python library for parsing, storing, and converting various file formats commonly used by quantum chemistry, molecular dynamics, and plane-wave density-functional-theory software programs.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] It also supports a flexible framework for generating input files for various software packages.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] For a complete list of supported formats, please go to https://iodata.readthedocs.io/en/latest/formats.html.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] A number of tools intended for viewing and editing molecular structures are able to read in files in a number of formats and write them out in other formats.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The tools JChemPaint (based on the Chemistry Development Kit), XDrawChem (based on OpenBabel), Chime, Jmol, Mol2mol and Discovery Studio fit into this category.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Here is a short list of sources of freely available molecular data.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] There are many more resources than listed here out there on the Internet.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Links to these sources are given in the references below.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] 2. eMolecules is a commercial database for molecular data.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The data includes a two-dimensional structure diagram and a smiles string for each compound. eMolecules supports fast substructure searching based on parts of the molecular structure.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] ChemExper is a commercial data base for molecular data.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The search results include a two-dimensional structure diagram and a mole file for many compounds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] New York University Library of 3-D Molecular Structures.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The US Environmental Protection Agency's The Distributed Structure-Searchable Toxicity (DSSTox) Database Network is a project of EPA's Computational Toxicology Program.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] The database provides SDF molecular files with a focus on carcinogenic and otherwise toxic substances.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/chemical-file-format] Databases for predicted protein and nucleic acid structures such as AlphaFold Protein Structure Database and Swiss-Model also provide PDB format download.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] Cheminformatics has been an active field in various guises since the 1970s and earlier, with activity in academic departments and commercial pharmaceutical research and development departments.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] The term chemoinformatics was defined in its application to drug discovery by F.K.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] Since then, both terms, cheminformatics and chemoinformatics, have been used, although, lexicographically, cheminformatics appears to be more frequently used, despite academics in Europe declaring for the variant chemoinformatics in 2006.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] In 2009, a prominent Springer journal in the field was founded by transatlantic executive editors named the Journal of Cheminformatics.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] Cheminformatics combines the scientific working fields of chemistry, computer science, and information science—for example in the areas of topology, chemical graph theory, information retrieval and data mining in the chemical space.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] Cheminformatics can also be applied to data analysis for various industries like paper and pulp, dyes and such allied industries.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] A primary application of cheminformatics is the storage, indexing, and search of information relating to chemical compounds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] The efficient search of such stored information includes topics that are dealt with in computer science, such as data mining, information retrieval, information extraction, and machine learning.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] The *in silico* representation of chemical structures uses specialized formats such as the Simplified molecular input line entry specifications (SMILES) or the XML-based Chemical Markup Language.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] These representations are often used for storage in large chemical databases.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] While some formats are suited for visual representations in two- or three-dimensions, others are more suited for studying physical interactions, modeling and docking studies.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] Chemical data can pertain to real or virtual molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] Virtual libraries of compounds may be generated in various ways to explore chemical space and hypothesize novel compounds with desired properties.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] Virtual libraries of classes of compounds (drugs, natural products, diversity-oriented synthetic products) were recently generated using the FOG (fragment optimized growth) algorithm.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] This was done by using cheminformatic tools to train transition probabilities of a Markov chain on authentic classes of compounds, and then using the Markov chain to generate novel compounds that were similar to the training database.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] In contrast to high-throughput screening, virtual screening involves computationally screening *in silico* libraries of compounds, by means of various methods such as docking, to identify members likely to possess desired properties such as biological activity against a given target.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] In some cases, combinatorial chemistry is used in the development of the library to increase the efficiency in mining the chemical space.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] More commonly, a diverse library of small molecules or natural products is screened.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] This is the calculation of quantitative structure–activity relationship and quantitative structure property relationship values, used to predict the activity of compounds from their structures.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] In this context there is also a strong relationship to chemometrics.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] Chemical expert systems are also relevant, since they represent parts of chemical knowledge as an *in silico* representation.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/cheminformatics] There is a relatively new concept of matched molecular pair analysis or prediction-driven MMPA which is coupled with QSAR model in order to identify activity cliff.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Beginning with the 2019.03 release, the RDKit is no longer supporting Python 2.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] If you need to continue using Python 2, please stick with a release from the 2018.09 release cycle.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] This document is intended to provide an overview of how one can use the RDKit functionality from Python.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] It’s not comprehensive and it’s not a manual.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Contributing to the documentation is a great service both to the RDKit community and to your future self.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] displays something like: `[12:20:41] Can't kekulize mol`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] By default a single reader thread is used to extract records from the file and a single writer thread is used to process them.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Note that due to multithreading the output may not be in the expected order.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Furthermore, the MultithreadedSmilesMolSupplier and the MultithreadedSDMolSupplier cannot be used as random-access objects.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Single molecules can be converted to text using several functions present in the `rdkit.Chem` module.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Note: as of this writing (Aug 2008), the smiles provided when one requests kekuleSmiles are not canonical.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The limitation is not in the SMILES generation, but in the kekulization itself.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] In order for atom or bond stereochemistry to be recognised correctly by most software, it’s essential that the mol block have atomic coordinates.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] It’s also convenient for many reasons, such as drawing the molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Generating a mol block for a molecule that does not have coordinates will, by default, automatically cause coordinates to be generated.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] These are not, however, stored with the molecule.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Coordinates can be generated and stored with the molecule using functionality in the `rdkit.Chem.AllChem` module (see the Chem vs AllChem section for more information).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Or you can add 3D coordinates by embedding the molecule (this uses the ETKDG method, which is described in more detail below).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Note that we add Hs to the molecule before generating the conformer.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Other available Writers include the `rdkit.Chem.rdmolfiles.SmilesWriter` and the `rdkit.Chem.rdmolfiles.TDTWriter`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] As the name indicates, this is a symmetrized SSSR; if you are interested in the number of “true” SSSR, use the GetSSSR function (note that in this case there’s no difference).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The distinction between symmetrized and non-symmetrized SSSR is discussed in more detail below in the section The SSSR Problem.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Normally molecules are stored in the RDKit with the hydrogen atoms implicit (e.g. not explicitly present in the molecular graph.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] RDKit molecules are usually stored with the bonds in aromatic rings having aromatic bond types.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] because the flags in the original molecule are not cleared (clearAromaticFlags defaults to False).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The value returned by *SanitizeMol()* indicates that no problems were encountered.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The RDKit has a library for generating depictions (sets of 2D) coordinates for molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The 2D conformer is constructed in a canonical orientation and is built to minimize intramolecular clashes, i.e. to maximize the clarity of the drawing.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Another option for Compute2DCoords allows you to generate 2D depictions for molecules that closely mimic 3D conformers.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] This is available using the function `rdkit.Chem.AllChem.GenerateDepictionMatching3DStructure()`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] More fine-grained control can be obtained using the core function `rdkit.Chem.rdDepictor.Compute2DCoordsMimicDistmat()`, but that is beyond the scope of this document.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] See the implementation of GenerateDepictionMatching3DStructure in AllChem.py for an example of how it is used.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The RDKit can generate conformers for molecules using two different methods.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The bounds matrix is smoothed using a triangle-bounds smoothing algorithm.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] A random distance matrix that satisfies the bounds matrix is generated.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] This distance matrix is embedded in 3D dimensions (producing coordinates for each atom).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The resulting coordinates are cleaned up somewhat using a crude force field and the bounds matrix.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Note that the conformers that result from this procedure tend to be fairly ugly.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] They should be cleaned up using a force field.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] More recently, there is an implementation of the ETKDG method of Riniker and Landrum [18] which uses torsion angle preferences from the Cambridge Structural Database (CSD) to correct the conformers after distance geometry has been used to generate them.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] With this method, there should be no need to use a minimisation step to clean up the structures.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] More detailed information about the conformer generator and the parameters controlling it can be found in the “RDKit Book”.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Since the 2018.09 release of the RDKit, ETKDG is the default conformer generation method.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Since the 2024.03 release ETKDGv3 is the default.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The RDKit also has an implementation of the MMFF94 force field available. [12], [13], [14], [15], [16] Please note that the MMFF atom typing code uses its own aromaticity model, so the aromaticity flags of the molecule will be modified after calling MMFF-related methods.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Note the calls to *Chem.AddHs()* in the examples above.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] By default RDKit molecules do not have H atoms explicitly present in the graph, but they are important for getting realistic geometries, so they generally should be added.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] They can always be removed afterwards if necessary with a call to *Chem.RemoveHs()*.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] With the RDKit, multiple conformers can also be generated using the different embedding methods.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] In both cases this is simply a matter of running the distance geometry calculation multiple times from different random start points.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The option *numConfs* allows the user to set the number of conformers that should be generated.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The conformers so generated can be aligned to each other and the RMS values calculated.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] rmslist contains the RMS values between the first conformer and all others.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The RMS between two specific conformers (e.g.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The flag prealigned lets the user specify if the conformers are already aligned (by default, the function aligns them).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The result is a list a containing 2-tuples: *(not_converged, energy)* for each conformer.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] If *not_converged* is 0, the minimization for that conformer converged.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Setting *numThreads* to zero causes the software to use the maximum number of threads allowed on your computer.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The RDKit pickle format is fairly compact and it is much, much faster to build a molecule from a pickle than from a Mol file or SMILES string, so storing molecules you will be working with repeatedly as pickles can be a good idea.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] These would of course look better if the common core were aligned.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Atoms in a molecule can be highlighted by drawing a coloured solid or open circle around them, and bonds likewise can have a coloured outline applied.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Atoms and bonds can also be highlighted with multiple colours if they fall into multiple sets, for example if they are matched by more than 1 substructure pattern.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] As of version 2020.03, it is possible to add arbitrary small strings to annotate atoms and bonds in the drawing.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The strings are added as properties `atomNote` and `bondNote` and they will be placed automatically close to the atom or bond in question in a manner intended to minimise their clash with the rest of the drawing.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] For convenience, here are 3 flags in `MolDraw2DOptions` that will add stereo information (R/S to atoms, E/Z to bonds) and atom and bond sequence numbers.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Note that you can use `<sup>` and `<sub>` in these labels to provide super- and subscripts.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Those are the atom indices in `m`, ordered as `patt`’s atoms.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Notice that when *useChirality* is set a non-chiral query **does** match a chiral molecule.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] It is possible to attach indices to the atoms in the SMARTS pattern.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] This is most often done in reaction SMARTS (see Chemical Reactions), but is more general than that.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] For example, in the SMARTS patterns for torsion angle analysis published by Guba *et al.* (`DOI: acs.jcim.5b00522`) indices are used to define the four atoms of the torsion of interest.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] This allows additional atoms to be used to define the environment of the four torsion atoms, as in `[cH0:1][c:2]([cH0])!@[CX3!r:3]=[NX2!r:4]` for an aromatic C=N torsion.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] We might wonder in passing why they didn’t use recursive SMARTS for this, which would have made life easier, but it is what it is.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The atom lists from `GetSubstructureMatches` are guaranteed to be in order of the SMARTS, but in this case we’ll get five atoms so we need a way of picking out, in the correct order, the four of interest.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Starting with the 2020.03 release, the RDKit allows you to provide an optional function that is used to check whether or not a possible substructure match should be accepted.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] This function is called with the molecule to be matched and the indices of the matching atoms.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Here’s an example of how you can use the functionality to do “Markush-like” matching, requiring that all atoms in a sidechain are either carbon (type “all_carbon”) or aren’t aromatic (type “alkyl”).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] The RDKit contains a number of functions for modifying molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] Note that these transformation functions are intended to provide an easy way to make simple modifications to molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] For more complex transformations, use the Chemical Reactions functionality.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] There’s a variety of functionality for using the RDKit’s substructure-matching machinery for doing quick molecular transformations.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] By default the sidechains are labeled based on the order they are found.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p01] `rdkit.Chem.rdmolops.ReplaceCore()` returns the sidechains in a single molecule.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] There are 2 methods for finding maximum common substructures.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The first, FindMCS, finds a single fragment maximum common substructure (MCS) of two or more molecules: The second, RascalMCES, finds the maximum common edge substructure (MCES) between two molecules and can return a multi-fragment MCES.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] It returns an MCSResult instance with information about the number of atoms and bonds in the MCS, the SMARTS string which matches the identified MCS, and a flag saying if the algorithm timed out.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] If no MCS is found then the number of atoms and bonds is set to 0 and the SMARTS to `''`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] By default, two atoms match if they are the same element and two bonds match if they have the same bond type.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The options for the atomCompare argument are: CompareAny says that any atom matches any other atom, CompareElements compares by element type, and CompareIsotopes matches based on the isotope label.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Isotope labels can be used to implement user-defined atom types.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] A substructure has both atoms and bonds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] By default, the algorithm attempts to maximize the number of bonds found.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] You can change this by setting the `maximizeBonds` argument to False.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Maximizing the number of bonds tends to maximize the number of rings, although two small rings may have fewer bonds than one large ring.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] You might not want a 3-valent nitrogen to match one which is 5-valent.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The default `matchValences` value of False ignores valence information.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] When True, the atomCompare setting is modified to also require that the two atoms have the same valency.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] It can be strange to see a linear carbon chain match a carbon ring, which is what the `ringMatchesRingOnly` default of False does.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] If you set it to True then ring bonds will only match ring bonds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Notice that the SMARTS returned now include ring queries on the atoms and bonds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] You can further restrict things and require that partial rings (as in this case) are not allowed.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] That is, if an atom is part of the MCS and the atom is in a ring of the entire molecule then that atom is also in a ring of the MCS.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Setting `completeRingsOnly` to True toggles this requirement.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The MCS algorithm will exhaustively search for a maximum common substructure.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Typically this takes a fraction of a second, but for some comparisons this can take minutes or longer.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Use the `timeout` parameter to stop the search after the given number of seconds (wall-clock seconds, not CPU seconds) and return the best match found in that time.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] If timeout is reached then the `canceled` property of the MCSResult will be True instead of False.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] It returns a list of RascalResult objects.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] There is also the method largestFragmentOnly(), which cuts the MCES down to the largest single fragment.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] This is a non-reversible change, so if you want both results, take a copy first.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] By default, the MCES algorithm returns the first result it finds of maximum size.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Because of symmetry, there may be other equivalent solutions with the same number of atoms and bonds, but with different equivalent bonds matched to each other.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] If you want to see all MCESs of maximum size, you can use the option allBestMCESs = True.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] This will increase the run time, partly because more branches in the search tree must be examined, but mostly because sorting the multiple results is quite time-consuming.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The results are returned in a consistent order sorted by number of bond matches, then number of fragments (fewer first), then largest fragment size and so on.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Some of these aren’t trivial to compute.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The adamantane example above is particularly extreme because not only is there extensive symmetry about the adamantane end and 2-fold symmetry at the phenyl end but also several points of breaking the matching alkyl chain all of which give rise to valid MCESs of the same size.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] In this case, sorting into a consistent order takes significantly longer than determining the MCESs in the first place.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The MCES differs from a conventional MCS in that it is the maximum common substructure based on bonds rather than atoms.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Often the result is the same, but not always.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The Johnson similarity is akin to a Tanimoto similarity, but expressed in terms of the atoms and bonds in the MCES.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] It is the square of the sum of the number of atoms and bonds in the MCES divided by the product of the sums of the numbers of atoms and bonds in the 2 input molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] It has values between 0.0 (no MCES between the molecules) and 1.0 (the molecules are identical).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] A key source of efficiency in the RASCAL algorithm is a fast and correct prediction of a maximum value for the Johnson similarity between 2 molecules and hence the maximum size of the MCES.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The first step in the algorithm is then a screening, whereby the full MCES determination is not performed if the predicted similarity is less than some desired threshold.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The final similarity between the 2 molecules may be less than the threshold, but it will never be higher than the predicted upper bound.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] RASCAL stems from RApid Similarity CALulation.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] In this case, the upper bound on the similarity score is below the default threshold of 0.7, so no results are returned.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Setting the threshold to 0.5 produces the second result although, as can be seen, the final similarity is substantially below the threshold.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] This example also shows a disadvantage of the MCES method, which is that it can produce small fragments in the MCES which are rarely helpful.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The option minFragSize can be used to over-ride the default value of -1, which means no minimum size.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] This result may look a bit odd, with a single aromatic carbon in the first SMARTS string.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] This is a consequence of the fact that the MCES works on matching bonds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] A better, atom-centric, representation might be C1CCC[$(C-c)]1.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] When the completeAromaticRings option is set to False, a larger MCES is found, with just the pyridine nitrogen atom not matching the corresponding phenyl carbon atom.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] There are 2 ways of getting an MCES that is just a single fragment.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The first is to use the option *opts.singleLargestFrag = True*.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The second is to use the method *opts.allBestMCESs*, find the result with the largest single fragment and use its *largestFragmentOnly*.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The two methods are equivalent - the first option does this internally.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The result of the singleLargestFrag option may not be the largest single possible fragment in common between the two molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The single largest fragment is thus the 3-propylpiperidine.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Which has a 10 atom, 9 bond fragment which cannot be part of a fragmented MCES of 12 bonds, so doesn’t appear in the Rascal results set.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] If you are sure you will only ever be interested in the single largest fragment in common, you should use rdFMCS.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] There are 2 clustering methods available using the Johnson metric.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The second, RascalButinaCluster, uses the Butina sphere-exclusion algorithm (Butina JCICS 39 747-750 (1999)).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Because of the time-consuming nature of the MCES determination, these clustering methods can be slow to run, so are best used on small sets (no more than a few hundred molecules) of small molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The RDKit has a variety of built-in functionality for generating molecular fingerprints and using them to calculate molecular similarity.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The most straightforward and consistent way to get fingerprints is to create a FingeprintGenerator object for your fingerprint type of interest and then use that to calculate fingerprints.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Note that there are older, legacy methods of generating fingerprints with the RDKit which are still supported, but these will not be covered here.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Available similarity metrics include Tanimoto, Dice, Cosine, Sokal, Russel, Kulczynski, McConnaughey, and Tversky.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] More details about the algorithm used for the RDKit fingerprint can be found in the “RDKit Book”.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Atom-pair descriptors [3] are available in several different forms.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Because the space of bits that can be included in atom-pair fingerprints is huge, they are stored in a sparse manner.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] It’s also possible to get atom-pair descriptors encoded as a standard bit vector fingerprint.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] This family of fingerprints, better known as circular fingerprints [5], is built by applying the Morgan algorithm to a set of user-supplied atom invariants.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The default atom invariants use connectivity information similar to those used for the well known ECFP family of fingerprints.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Feature-based invariants, similar to those used for the FCFP fingerprints, can also be used by creating the fingerprint generator with an appropriate atom invariant generator.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The feature definitions used are defined in the section Feature Definitions Used in the Morgan Fingerprints.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] When comparing the ECFP/FCFP fingerprints and the Morgan fingerprints generated by the RDKit, remember that the 4 in ECFP4 corresponds to the diameter of the atom environments considered, while the Morgan fingerprints take a radius parameter.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] So the examples above, with radius=2, are roughly equivalent to ECFP4 and FCFP4.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The user can also provide their own atom invariants using the optional `customAtomInvariants` argument to the `GetFingerprint()` call.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] There is a SMARTS-based implementation of the 166 public MACCS keys.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] This is not currently supported by the RDKit’s fingerprint generators, so you have to use a different interface.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The MACCS keys were critically evaluated and compared to other MACCS implementations in Q3 2008.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] In cases where the public keys are fully defined, things looked pretty good.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The fingerprint generators can collect information about the atoms/bonds involved in setting bits when a fingerprint is generated.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] This information is quite useful for understanding which parts of a molecule were involved in each bit.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Each fingerprinting method provides different information, but this is all accessed using the additionalOutput argument to the fingerprinting functions.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Information is available about the atoms that contribute to particular bits in the Morgan fingerprint via the bit info map.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] This is a dictionary with one entry per bit set in the fingerprint, the keys are the bit ids, the values are lists of (atom index, radius) tuples.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Interpreting the above: bit 98513984 is set twice: once by atom 1 and once by atom 2, each at radius 1.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Bit 4048591891 is set once by atom 5 at radius 2.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Information is available about the bond paths that contribute to particular bits in the RDKit fingerprint via the bit info map.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] This is a dictionary with one entry per bit set in the fingerprint, the keys are the bit ids, the values are tuples of tuples containing bond indices.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Those last two examples, which each correspond to the path containing bonds 0 and 1, demonstrate that by default each path sets two bits in the RDKit fingerprint.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Note that in cases where the same bit is set by multiple atoms in the molecule (as for bit 1553 for the RDKit fingerprint in the example above), the drawing functions will display the first example.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] A common task is to pick a small subset of diverse molecules from a larger set.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The RDKit provides a number of approaches for doing this in the `rdkit.SimDivFilters` module.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] If we aren’t working with bit vector fingerprints, we can also do a diversity pick by providing our own distance matrix to the algorithm.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Similarity maps are a way to visualize the atomic contributions to the similarity between a molecule and a reference molecule.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The methodology is described in Ref. [17] .
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The SimilarityMaps module supports three kind of fingerprints: atom pairs, topological torsions and Morgan fingerprints.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The types of atom pairs and torsions are normal (default), hashed and bit vector (bv).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The types of the Morgan fingerprint are bit vector (bv, default) and count vector (count).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The function generating a similarity map for two fingerprints requires the specification of the fingerprint function and optionally the similarity metric.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The default for the latter is the Dice similarity.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] For a different type of Morgan (e.g. count) and radius = 1 instead of 2, as well as a different similarity metric (e.g.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The convenience function GetSimilarityMapForFingerprint involves the normalisation of the atomic weights such that the maximum absolute weight is 1.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Therefore, the function outputs the maximum weight that was found when creating the map.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] A variety of descriptors are available within the RDKit.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The complete list is provided in List of Available Descriptors.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The `rdkit.Chem.Descriptors` module provides a convenience function, `CalcMolDescriptors()`, to calculate all available descriptors for a molecule.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Similarity maps can be used to visualize descriptors that can be divided into atomic contributions.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The RDKit also supports applying chemical reactions to sets of molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The RDKit’s MolDraw2D-based rendering can also handle chemical reactions.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Sometimes, particularly when working with rxn files, it is difficult to express a reaction exactly enough to not end up with extraneous products.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The RDKit provides a method of “protecting” atoms to disallow them from taking part in reactions.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] This can be demonstrated re-using the amide-bond formation reaction used above.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The query for amines isn’t specific enough, so it matches any nitrogen that has at least one H attached.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The first product corresponds to the reaction at the amide N.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] We can prevent this from happening by protecting all amide Ns.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Associated with the chemical reaction functionality is an implementation of the Recap algorithm. [8] Recap uses a set of chemical transformations mimicking common reactions carried out in the lab in order to decompose a molecule into a series of reasonable fragments.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Notice that dummy atoms are used to mark points where the molecule was fragmented.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Notice that RDKit BRICS implementation returns the unique fragments generated from a molecule and that the dummy atoms are tagged to indicate which type of reaction applies.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] By default those results come back in a random order (technically the example above will always return the same results since we seeded Python’s random number generator just before calling BRICSBuild()).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] In addition to the methods described above, the RDKit provide a very flexible generic function for fragmenting molecules along user-specified bonds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] Here’s a quick demonstration of using that to break all bonds between atoms in rings and atoms not in rings.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] By default the attachment points are labelled (using isotopes) with the index of the atom that was removed.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] We can also provide our own set of atom labels in the form of pairs of unsigned integers.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p02] The first value in each pair is used as the label for the dummy that replaces the bond’s begin atom, the second value in each pair is for the dummy that replaces the bond’s end atom.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Chemical features in the RDKit are defined using a SMARTS-based feature definition language (described in detail in the RDKit book).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Combining a set of chemical features with the 2D (topological) distances between them gives a 2D pharmacophore.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] When the distances are binned, unique integer ids can be assigned to each of these pharmacophores and they can be stored in a fingerprint.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Details of the encoding are in the The RDKit Book.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Another possible set of feature definitions for 2D pharmacophore fingerprints in the RDKit are those published by Gobbi and Poppinger. [10] The module `rdkit.Chem.Pharm2D.Gobbi_Pharm2D` has a pre-configured signature factory for these fingerprint types.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The RDKit contains a collection of tools for fragmenting molecules and working with those fragments.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Fragments are defined to be made up of a set of connected atoms that may have associated functional groups.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The fragments are stored as entries in a `rdkit.Chem.rdfragcatalog.FragCatalog`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Notice that the entry descriptions include pieces in angular brackets (e.g. between ‘<’ and ‘>’).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] These describe the functional groups attached to the fragment.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] For example, in the above example, the catalog entry 0 corresponds to an ethyl fragment with an alcohol attached to one of the carbons and entry 1 is an ethylene with a carboxylic acid on one carbon.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The catalog is hierarchical: smaller fragments are combined to form larger ones.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The rest of the machinery associated with fingerprints can now be applied to these fragment fingerprints.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The columns above are: bitId, infoGain, nInactive, nActive.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Note that this approach isn’t particularly effective for this artificial example.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The *unmatched* return value has the indices of the molecules that did not match a core; in this case there are none.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The other result is a list with one dict for each molecule; each dict contains the core that matched the molecule (in this case there was only one) and the molecule’s R groups.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] R-group decomposition is actually pretty complex, so there’s a lot more there.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Hopefully this is enough to get you started.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] A number of companies, notably Enamine and ChemSpace, provide very large libraries of compounds in synthon form.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Enumerating and searching them is infeasible due to their enormous sizes, on the order of 10s of billions of compounds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] They can, however, be searched efficiently in synthon form.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] which describes a library of amides built from 2 synthons.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] There are 4 examples for the first synthon and 3 for the second, giving a total of 12 products.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Each product is formed by taking a synthon from the first set and another from the second and combining them by removing the attachment atoms ([1*] in this case), and adding a bond between the atoms the attachment atoms were bonded to.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Both Enamine and ChemSpace use transuranic elements (uranium, neptunium, plutonium and americium) as the attachment atoms.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Libraries with up to 4 synthons per product are supported.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] In order to perform the search, the query molecule is fragmented by cutting all combinations of bonds that give rise to a maximum number of fragments.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The maximum is the largest number of synthon sets in any reaction in the space, and will most likely be between 2 and 4.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] There is not a maximum on the number of bonds used in the cutting, because 2 non-ring bonds will give rise to 3 fragments, but 4 ring bonds may also do so, 2 splitting one ring and the other 2 a different ring in the query.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] This produces a large number of fragment sets, where each set is produced by cutting one particular combination of bonds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Each fragment in the set is compared with synthons in one column of the synthons for each reaction thus identifying combinations of synthons that might match the query.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] These combinations are enumerated and a final comparison with the query performed to select the hit set.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The algorithm is largely similar to that described by Liphardt and Sander.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] However, a large amount of pre-processing is required before the data are searchable which can be time consuming.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] For example, preparing the current REAL database (2024-09) of 70 billion compounds can take several hours.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] It is therefore strongly recommended that a binary database is created before use.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The fingerprints are written to the DB file, which means that the file must be searched using exactly the same type in order to get meaningful results.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] You may need to keep several versions of the database, labelled accordingly.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] although under the hood it does exactly the same steps.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The 2024-09 REAL database requires about 10GB of RAM, FreedomSpace 2024-09 about 3.5GB.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] They should both therefore be searchable on an average laptop.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Any query molecule can be used for substructure searching.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The full set of query features supported by the RDKit is allowed.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] However, queries that use recursive SMARTS or other more complicated features may be noticeably slower.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Results are returned in a *rdSynthonSpaceSearch.SearchResults* object.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Substructure searches should take no more than a few seconds on a machine with average performance, although this will depend on the generality and complexity of the query and the number of hits returned.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The timeout is specified in seconds; if the given time is exceeded all results found thus far will be returned.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The method *results.GetTimedOut()* will report whether or not that has occurred.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The *maxHits* parameter defaults to 1000.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] If set to -1, all hits will be returned.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] It can happen that having looked at the first 1000 hits, you may wish to examine the following 1000 in the hit list.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] As well as returning the first hits, the parameter *randomSample*, if set True, will return a random sampling of the possible hits.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The synthon space can also be searched by fingerprint similarity.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The fingerprint generator used to make the query fingerprints must be exactly the same as that used to create the DB file.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The SynthonSpace can report the infoString of the fingerprint generator it was used with, which will help if there is a mismatch.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] At present there is no way of using the infoString directly to create a fingerprint generator, so it must be examined visually.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The similarity metric is hard-coded to use the Tanimoto coefficient.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The default similarity cutoff for the search is 0.5, which is a reasonable starting value for a Morgan fingerprint of radius 2.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Note that in the similarity search, you will get the first *maxHits* hits that pass the threshold, not necessarily the best hits.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The search attempts to bring the most similar matches towards the start of the hit list by ordering the synthons that match a fragment in descending order of similarity, but this does not always bring the most similar products to the fore.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Once the search has assembled a set of likely synthon combinations that might match the query by similarity, a two stage screen is used.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The fingerprints of the synthons are added together and the Tanimoto similarity to the query fingerprint calculated.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] If this is above the threshold then the hit molecule is made, a fingerprint generated and that compared with the query fingerprint.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] If that similarity passes the threshold, the hit is accepted.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The first, approximate, comparison may cause genuine hits to be missed, so there is a parameter *approxSimilarityAdjuster* that lowers the threshold for the first test.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The higher the value the fewer hits will be missed, but at the expense of longer search times.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The sizes of the hits can be limited by setting appropriate values to the SynthonSpaceSearchParams object.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Maximum and minimum values can be set for the number of heavy atoms, the number of chiral atoms and the molecular weight.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Bit vectors are containers for efficiently storing a set number of binary values, e.g. for fingerprints.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] There is a reasonable amount of documentation available within from the RDKit’s docstrings.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] When working in an environment that does command completion or tooltips, one can see the available methods quite easily.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The RDKit also has functionality enabling batch edits of molecules which provides a more efficient way to remove multiple atoms or bonds at once.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] It is even easier to generate nonsense using the RWMol than it is with standard molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] If you need chemically reasonable results, be certain to sanitize the results.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The majority of “basic” chemical functionality (e.g. reading/writing molecules, substructure searching, molecular cleanup, etc.) is in the `rdkit.Chem` module.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] More advanced, or less frequently used, functionality is in `rdkit.Chem.AllChem`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The distinction has been made to speed startup and lower import times; there’s no sense in loading the 2D->3D library and force field implementation if one is only interested in reading and writing a couple of molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] As others have ranted about with more energy and eloquence than I intend to, the definition of a molecule’s smallest set of smallest rings is not unique.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] In some high symmetry molecules, a “true” SSSR will give results that are unappealing.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] For example, the SSSR for cubane only contains 5 rings, even though there are “obviously” 6.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] This problem can be fixed by implementing a *small* (instead of *smallest*) set of smallest rings algorithm that returns symmetric results.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] This is the approach that we took with the RDKit in `rdkit.Chem.GetSymmSSSR()`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Because it is sometimes useful to know the “true” SSSR rings, there is a `rdkit.Chem.GetSSSR()` function which returns this potentially non-unique set of rings.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] These all require the molecule to have a 3D conformer.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] These are adapted from the definitions in Gobbi, A. & Poppinger, D. “Genetic optimization of combinatorial libraries.” *Biotechnology and Bioengineering* **61**, 47-54 (1998).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Several sets of rules exist for estimating the likelihood of a molecule exhibiting drug-like behaviour.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] It’s worth noting that these are rules of thumb, and that many examples of approved small molecule drugs exist that disobey these rules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Lipinski’s “Rule of 5” [19] was introduced to estimate the oral bioavailability of molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Pan Assay Interference Compounds (or PAINS) [20] are molecules that display non-specific binding, leading to unwanted side effects and false-positives in virtual screening.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] Common PAINS motifs include toxoflavin, isothiazolones, hydroxyphenyl hydrazones, curcumin, phenolsulfonamides, rhodanines, enones, quinones, and catechols.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The Brenk filter [21] removes molecules containing substructures with undesirable pharmacokinetics or toxicity.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] These include sulfates and phosphates that contribute to unfavourable pharmacokinetics, nitro groups which are mutagenic and 2-halopyridines and thiols which are both reactive.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The NIH filter [22], [23] defined a list of functional groups with undesirable properties.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] All of the available filters can also be considered at once.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] This work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 4.0 License.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] To view a copy of this license, visit http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/ or send a letter to Creative Commons, 543 Howard Street, 5th Floor, San Francisco, California, 94105, USA.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/gettingstartedinpython-p03] The intent of this license is similar to that of the RDKit itself.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The **International Chemical Identifier** (**InChI**, pronounced /ˈɪntʃiː/ *IN-chee*) is a textual identifier for chemical substances, designed to provide a standard way to encode molecular information and to facilitate the search for such information in databases and on the web.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Initially developed by the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) and National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) from 2000 to 2005, the format and algorithms are non-proprietary.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Since May 2009, it has been developed by the **InChI Trust**, a nonprofit charity from the United Kingdom which works to implement and promote the use of InChI.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The identifiers describe chemical substances in terms of *layers* of information — the atoms and their bond connectivity, tautomeric information, isotope information, stereochemistry, and electronic charge information.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Not all layers have to be provided; for instance, the tautomer layer can be omitted if that type of information is not relevant to the particular application.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The InChI algorithm converts input structural information into a unique InChI identifier in a three-step process: normalization (to remove redundant information), canonicalization (to generate a unique number label for each atom), and serialization (to give a string of characters).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] InChIs can thus be seen as akin to a general and extremely formalized version of IUPAC names.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] They can express more information than the simpler SMILES notation and, in contrast to SMILES strings, every structure has a unique InChI string, which is important in database applications.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Information about the 3-dimensional coordinates of atoms is not represented in InChI; for this purpose a format such as PDB can be used.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The InChIKey, sometimes referred to as a hashed InChI, is a fixed length (27 character) condensed digital representation of the InChI that is not human-understandable.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The InChIKey specification was released in September 2007 in order to facilitate web searches for chemical compounds, since these were problematic with the full-length InChI.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Unlike the InChI, the InChIKey is not unique: though collisions are expected to be extremely rare, there are known collisions.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] A major milestone was version 1.02 of January 2009, which provided a means to generate so called *standard InChI*, a version of the InChI with a fixed level of detail and collection of layers.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The standard InChIKey is then the hashed version of the standard InChI string.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The standard InChI will simplify comparison of InChI strings and keys generated by different groups, and subsequently accessed via diverse sources such as databases and web resources.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Since version 1.07.1 (August 2024), the software uses the MIT license, and may be downloaded from the InChI GitHub site.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Beside the implementation in molecule editors, stand-alone executables have been packaged for multiple Linux distributions, including Debian.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] In order to avoid generating different InChIs for tautomeric structures, before generating the InChI, an input chemical structure is normalized to reduce it to its so-called core parent structure.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] This may involve changing bond orders, rearranging formal charges and possibly adding and removing protons.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Different input structures may give the same result; for example, acetic acid and acetate would both give the same core parent structure, that of acetic acid.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] A core parent structure may be disconnected, consisting of more than one component, in which case the sublayers in the InChI usually consist of sublayers for each component, separated by semicolons (periods for the chemical formula sublayer).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] One way this can happen is that all metal atoms are disconnected during normalization; so, for example, the InChI for tetraethyllead will have five components, one for lead and four for the ethyl groups.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] If present, the stereochemical layer, with sublayers `b`, `/t`, `/m` and `/s`, gives stereochemical information, and the isotopic layer `/i` (which may contain sublayers `/h`, `/b`, `/t`, `/m` and `/s`) gives isotopic information.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] These are the only layers which can occur in a standard InChI.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] This may contain various sublayers, including `/f`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Every InChI starts with the string `InChI=` followed by the version number, currently `1`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] If the InChI is standard, this is followed by the letter `S` for **standard InChIs**, which is a fully standardized InChI flavor maintaining the same level of attention to structure details and the same conventions for drawing perception.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The remaining information is structured as a sequence of layers and sub-layers, with each layer providing one specific type of information.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The layers and sub-layers are separated by the delimiter `/` and start with a characteristic prefix letter (except for the chemical formula sub-layer of the main layer).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Fixed-H layer (`/f`) for tautomeric hydrogens; contains some or all of the above types of layers except atom connections; may end with `o` sublayer.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The delimiter-prefix format has the advantage that a user can easily use a wildcard search to find identifiers that match only in certain layers.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The condensed, 27 character **InChIKey** is a hashed version of the full InChI (using the SHA-256 algorithm), designed to allow for easy web searches of chemical compounds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The **standard InChIKey** is the hashed counterpart of **standard InChI**.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Most chemical structures on the Web up to 2007 have been represented as GIF files, which are not searchable for chemical content.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The full InChI turned out to be too lengthy for easy searching, and therefore the InChIKey was developed.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] There is a very small, but nonzero chance of two different molecules having the same InChIKey, but the probability for duplication of only the first 14 characters has been estimated as only one duplication in 75 databases each containing one billion unique structures.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] With all databases currently having below 50 million structures, such duplication appears unlikely at present.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] A recent study more extensively studies the collision rate finding that the experimental collision rate is in agreement with the theoretical expectations.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The InChIKey currently consists of three parts separated by hyphens, of 14, 10 and one character(s), respectively, like `xxxxxxxxxxxxxx-yyyyyyyyfv-p`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The following are examples of InChIs and InChIKeys.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Because all standard InChIs can be trivially turned "nonstandard" by removing the "S" marker, they actually imply two keys that differ by one character.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] InChIKey uses a base 26 encoding to represent (parts of) SHA-256 hashes.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Input is chopped in 14-bit segments, each of which corresponds to three letters (triplets).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] A remaining group up to 9 bits correspond to 2 characters (doublets).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] In InChIKey, inputs can only be of two lengths: 65 bits for the "major" hash (divided into 14 × 4 + 9 bits for 3 × 4 + 2 = 14 characters) and 37 bits for the "minor" hash (14 × 2 + 9 bits for 3 × 2 + 2 = 8 characters).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The first 80 bits of the SHA-256 for an empty string is `e3 b0 c4 42 98 fc 1c 14 9a fb`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] This results in the following base26 strings for this hash: `UHFF`, `UHFFFAOY`, `UHFFFADPSC`, `UHFFFADPSCTJ`, `UHFFFADPSCTJAU`, `UHFFFADPSCTJAUYIS`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] These strings are commonly encountered when the corresponding layers have no data.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] For example, one sees `UHFFFAOYSA` or `UHFFFAOYNA` in an InChIKey when the source InChI has no stereochemical information.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] As the InChI cannot be reconstructed from the InChIKey, an InChIKey always needs to be linked to the original InChI to get back to the original structure.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] InChI Resolvers act as a lookup service to make these links, and prototype services are available from National Cancer Institute, the UniChem service at the European Bioinformatics Institute, and PubChem.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] ChemSpider has had a resolver until July 2015 when it was decommissioned.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The auxiliary information (`AuxInfo`) string is produced by InChI software alongside the InChI string.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The InChI user guide describes the format in detail.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The full complement of tags are: `1/0/N/E/gE/it/iN/I/E/gE/it/iN/CRV/rA/rB/rC`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] RInChI (Reaction InChI, International chemical identifier for reactions) is a standard method for using InChI to describe chemical reactions.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] An RInChI string consists of several sets of InChI strings for the reactants, products, and agents as well as information required to tag them as such.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] As shown above, layers that do not involve InChI parts are separated with `/` as in InChI.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Multiple InChI parts are separated with `!`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] It is allowed to omit some structures in the RInChI.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] In this case a sixth layer is used to specify how many structures have been omitted in each of layers 2, 3, and 4.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] RInChI has an analogous concept of *RInChIKeys'*.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] MInChI (Mixtures InChI, International chemical identifier for mixtures) is a draft standard for using (partial) InChI to describe a mixture.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] An example of a relatively complex (nested) Mixfile is provided below.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] It is also possible to create mixfiles with missing chemical formulae and generate MInChI from them; the "third part" of MInChI is intended to adapt to such situations.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] For more examples, readers can visit the MInChI Demo page.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The "Create MInChI" button generates MInChI.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Right-clicking on a node and choosing "copy branch" produces its Mixfile representation in the clipboard.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The format was originally called IChI (IUPAC Chemical Identifier), then renamed in July 2004 to INChI (IUPAC-NIST Chemical Identifier), and renamed again in November 2004 to InChI (IUPAC International Chemical Identifier), a trademark of IUPAC.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Scientific direction of the InChI standard is carried out by the IUPAC Division VIII Subcommittee, and funding of subgroups investigating and defining the expansion of the standard is carried out by both IUPAC and the InChI Trust.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The InChI Trust funds the development, testing and documentation of the InChI.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Current extensions are being defined to handle polymers and mixtures, Markush structures, isotopologues and isotopomers, reactions, organometallics, and nanomaterials, and once accepted by the Division VIII Subcommittee will be added to the algorithm.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The continuing development of the standard has been supported since 2010 by the not-for-profit **InChI Trust**, of which IUPAC is a member.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] Version 1.06 and was released in December 2020.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The InChI Trust has developed software to generate the InChI, InChIKey and other identifiers.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The release history of this software follows.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] The InChI has been adopted by many larger and smaller databases, including ChemSpider, ChEMBL, Golm Metabolome Database, and PubChem.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/international-chemical-identifier] However, the adoption is not straightforward, and many databases show a discrepancy between the chemical structures and the InChI they contain, which is a problem for linking databases.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] The outspread of artificial intelligence and machine learning to computational chemistry has also lead to various attempts to uncover new descriptors or to find the most predictive ones among some sort of candidates.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] Invariance to molecular numbering or labeling is assumed as a minimal basic requirement for any descriptor.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] Two other important invariance properties, translational invariance and rotational invariance, are the invariance of a descriptor value to any translation or rotation of the molecules in the chosen reference frame.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] These last invariance properties are required for the 3D-descriptors.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] This property refers to the ability of a descriptor to avoid equal values for different molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] In this sense, descriptors can show no degeneracy at all, low, intermediate, or high degeneracy.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] For example, the number of molecule atoms and the molecular weights are high degeneracy descriptors, while, usually, 3D-descriptors show low or no degeneracy at all.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] Molecular descriptors are numerical values that encapsulate chemical information about molecules, facilitating their mathematical analysis.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] Given the vast array of available descriptors, it's essential to establish foundational principles to ensure their reliability and utility.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] Should not be based on experimental properties 9.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] The initial set of principles ensures that a descriptor is well-defined and invariant to manipulations that don't alter the intrinsic molecular structure.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] Historically, many descriptors were designed for small organic molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] However, contemporary challenges necessitate descriptors that can be applied to diverse compounds, including salts, ionic liquids, peptides, polymers, and nanostructures.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] The subsequent set of guidelines emphasizes the descriptor's practical utility.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] An effective descriptor should be interpretable, correlate with experimental properties, and provide unique information not captured by other descriptors.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] Continuity and low degeneracy are crucial, as they ensure the descriptor can sensitively reflect minor structural variations.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] Ultimately, the information a descriptor provides is contingent upon the chosen molecular representation and its alignment with the specific property or activity being studied.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] Here there is a list of a selection of commercial and free descriptor calculation tools.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/molecular-descriptor] Official version discontinued (last update 2019), but has a community-maintained fork.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] In QSAR modeling, the predictors consist of physico-chemical properties or theoretical molecular descriptors of chemicals; the QSAR response-variable could be a biological activity of the chemicals.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] QSAR models first summarize a supposed relationship between chemical structures and biological activity in a data-set of chemicals.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Second, QSAR models predict the activities of new chemicals.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Related terms include **quantitative structure–property relationships** (QSPR) when a chemical property is modeled as the response variable.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] "Different properties or behaviors of chemical molecules have been investigated in the field of QSPR.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] As an example, biological activity can be expressed quantitatively as the concentration of a substance required to give a certain biological response.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Additionally, when physicochemical properties or structures are expressed by numbers, one can find a mathematical relationship, or quantitative structure-activity relationship, between the two.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The mathematical expression, if carefully validated, can then be used to predict the modeled response of other chemical structures.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The error includes model error (bias) and observational variability, that is, the variability in observations even on a correct model.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The basic assumption for all molecule-based hypotheses is that similar molecules have similar activities.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] This principle is also called Structure–Activity Relationship (SAR).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The underlying problem is therefore how to define a *small* difference on a molecular level, since each kind of activity, e.g. reaction ability, biotransformation ability, solubility, target activity, and so on, might depend on another difference.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Examples were given in the bioisosterism reviews by Patanie/LaVoie and Brown.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] In general, one is more interested in finding strong trends.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Created hypotheses usually rely on a finite number of chemicals, so care must be taken to avoid overfitting: the generation of hypotheses that fit training data very closely but perform poorly when applied to new data.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The *SAR paradox* refers to the fact that it is not the case that all similar molecules have similar activities.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Analogously, the "partition coefficient"—a measurement of differential solubility and itself a component of QSAR predictions—can be predicted either by atomic methods (known as "XLogP" or "ALogP") or by chemical fragment methods (known as "CLogP" and other variations).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] It has been shown that the logP of compound can be determined by the sum of its fragments; fragment-based methods are generally accepted as better predictors than atomic-based methods.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Fragmentary values have been determined statistically, based on empirical data for known logP values.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] This method gives mixed results and is generally not trusted to have accuracy of more than ±0.1 units.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Group or fragment-based QSAR is also known as GQSAR.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] GQSAR allows flexibility to study various molecular fragments of interest in relation to the variation in biological response.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The molecular fragments could be substituents at various substitution sites in congeneric set of molecules or could be on the basis of pre-defined chemical rules in case of non-congeneric sets.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] GQSAR also considers cross-terms fragment descriptors, which could be helpful in identification of key fragment interactions in determining variation of activity.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Lead discovery using fragnomics is an emerging paradigm.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] In this context FB-QSAR proves to be a promising strategy for fragment library design and in fragment-to-lead identification endeavours.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] An advanced approach on fragment or group-based QSAR based on the concept of pharmacophore-similarity is developed.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] This method, pharmacophore-similarity-based QSAR (PS-QSAR) uses topological pharmacophoric descriptors to develop QSAR models.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] This activity prediction may assist the contribution of certain pharmacophore features encoded by respective fragments toward activity improvement and/or detrimental effects.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The acronym **3D-QSAR** or **3-D QSAR** refers to the application of force field calculations requiring three-dimensional structures of a given set of small molecules with known activities (training set).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The training set needs to be superimposed (aligned) by either experimental data (e.g. based on ligand-protein crystallography) or molecule superimposition software.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] It uses computed potentials, e.g. the Lennard-Jones potential, rather than experimental constants and is concerned with the overall molecule rather than a single substituent.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The first 3-D QSAR was named Comparative Molecular Field Analysis (CoMFA) by Cramer et al.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] It examined the steric fields (shape of the molecule) and the electrostatic fields which were correlated by means of partial least squares regression (PLS).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The created data space is then usually reduced by a following feature extraction (see also dimensionality reduction).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The following learning method can be any of the already mentioned machine learning methods, e.g. support vector machines.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] An alternative approach uses multiple-instance learning by encoding molecules as sets of data instances, each of which represents a possible molecular conformation.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] A label or response is assigned to each set corresponding to the activity of the molecule, which is assumed to be determined by at least one instance in the set (i.e. some conformation of the molecule).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] On June 18, 2011 the Comparative Molecular Field Analysis (CoMFA) patent has dropped any restriction on the use of GRID and partial least-squares (PLS) technologies.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] In this approach, descriptors quantifying various electronic, geometric, or steric properties of a molecule are computed and used to develop a QSAR.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] This approach is different from the fragment (or group contribution) approach in that the descriptors are computed for the system as whole rather than from the properties of individual fragments.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] This approach is different from the 3D-QSAR approach in that the descriptors are computed from scalar quantities (e.g., energies, geometric parameters) rather than from 3D fields.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] An example of this approach is the QSARs developed for olefin polymerization by half sandwich compounds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] It has been shown that activity prediction is even possible based purely on the SMILES string.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Similarly to string-based methods, the molecular graph can directly be used as input for QSAR models, but usually yield inferior performance compared to descriptor-based QSAR models.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] QSAR has been merged with the similarity-based read-across technique to develop a new field of q-RASAR.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The DTC Laboratory at Jadavpur University has developed this hybrid method and the details are available at their laboratory page.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Recently, the q-RASAR framework has been improved by its integration with the ARKA descriptors in QSAR.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] In the literature it can be often found that chemists have a preference for partial least squares (PLS) methods, since it applies the feature extraction and induction in one step.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Computer SAR models typically calculate a relatively large number of features.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Because those lack structural interpretation ability, the preprocessing steps face a feature selection problem (i.e., which structural features should be interpreted to determine the structure-activity relationship).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Feature selection can be accomplished by visual inspection (qualitative selection by a human); by data mining; or by molecule mining.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] A typical data mining based prediction uses e.g. support vector machines, decision trees, artificial neural networks for inducing a predictive learning model.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Molecule mining approaches, a special case of structured data mining approaches, apply a similarity matrix based prediction or an automatic fragmentation scheme into molecular substructures.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Furthermore, there exist also approaches using maximum common subgraph searches or graph kernels.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Typically QSAR models derived from non linear machine learning is seen as a "black box", which fails to guide medicinal chemists.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Recently there is a relatively new concept of matched molecular pair analysis or prediction driven MMPA which is coupled with QSAR model in order to identify activity cliffs.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] QSARs are being applied in many disciplines, for example: risk assessment, toxicity prediction, and regulatory decisions in addition to drug discovery and lead optimization.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Obtaining a good quality QSAR model depends on many factors, such as the quality of input data, the choice of descriptors and statistical methods for modeling and for validation.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Any QSAR modeling should ultimately lead to statistically robust and predictive models capable of making accurate and reliable predictions of the modeled response of new compounds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] 4. data randomization or Y-scrambling for verifying the absence of chance correlation between the response and the modeling descriptors.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The success of any QSAR model depends on accuracy of the input data, selection of appropriate descriptors and statistical tools, and most importantly validation of the developed model.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Validation is the process by which the reliability and relevance of a procedure are established for a specific purpose; for QSAR models validation must be mainly for robustness, prediction performances and applicability domain (AD) of the models.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Some validation methodologies can be problematic.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] For example, *leave one-out* cross-validation generally leads to an overestimation of predictive capacity.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Even with external validation, it is difficult to determine whether the selection of training and test sets was manipulated to maximize the predictive capacity of the model being published.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Different aspects of validation of QSAR models that need attention include methods of selection of training set compounds, setting training set size and impact of variable selection for training set models for determining the quality of prediction.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Development of novel validation parameters for judging quality of QSAR models is also important.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] One of the first historical QSPR applications (as pre-condition to QSAR) was to predict boiling points.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] It is well known for instance that within a particular family of chemical compounds, especially of organic chemistry, that there are strong correlations between structure and observed properties.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] A simple example is the relationship between the number of carbons in alkanes and their boiling points.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] There is a clear trend in the increase of boiling point with an increase in the number carbons, and this serves as a means for predicting the boiling points of higher alkanes.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] A still very interesting application is the Hammett equation, Taft equation and pKa prediction methods.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The biological activity of molecules is usually measured in assays to establish the level of inhibition of particular signal transduction or metabolic pathways.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Drug discovery often involves the use of QSAR to identify chemical structures that could have good inhibitory effects on specific targets and have low toxicity (non-specific activity).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Of special interest is the prediction of partition coefficient log *P*, which is an important measure used in identifying "druglikeness" according to Lipinski's Rule of Five.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] While many quantitative structure activity relationship analyses involve the interactions of a family of molecules with an enzyme or receptor binding site, QSAR can also be used to study the interactions between the structural domains of proteins.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Protein-protein interactions can be quantitatively analyzed for structural variations resulted from site-directed mutagenesis.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] It is part of the machine learning method to reduce the risk for a SAR paradox, especially taking into account that only a finite amount of data is available (see also MVUE).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] In general, all QSAR problems can be divided into coding and learning.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] (Q)SAR models have been used for risk management.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] QSARS are suggested by regulatory authorities; in the European Union, QSARs are suggested by the REACH regulation, where "REACH" abbreviates "Registration, Evaluation, Authorisation and Restriction of Chemicals".
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Regulatory application of QSAR methods includes *in silico* toxicological assessment of genotoxic impurities.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Commonly used QSAR assessment software such as DEREK or CASE Ultra (MultiCASE) is used to genotoxicity of impurity according to ICH M7.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The chemical descriptor space whose convex hull is generated by a particular training set of chemicals is called the training set's applicability domain.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] Prediction of properties of novel chemicals that are located outside the applicability domain uses extrapolation, and so is less reliable (on average) than prediction within the applicability domain.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The assessment of the reliability of QSAR predictions remains a research topic, as a unified strategy has yet to be adopted by modellers and regulatory authorities.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/quantitative-structure-activity-relationship] The QSAR equations can be used to predict biological activities of newer molecules before their synthesis.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The **Simplified Molecular Input Line Entry System** (**SMILES**) is a specification in the form of a line notation for describing the structure of chemical species using short ASCII strings.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] SMILES strings can be imported by most molecule editors for conversion back into two-dimensional drawings or three-dimensional models of the molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The original SMILES specification was initiated in the 1980s.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] It has since been modified and extended.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] In 2007, an open standard called OpenSMILES was developed in the open source chemistry community to harmonize the different dialects.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The original SMILES specification was initiated by David Weininger at the USEPA Mid-Continent Ecology Division Laboratory in Duluth, Minnesota in the 1980s.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] It has since been modified and extended by others, most notably by Daylight Chemical Information Systems.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] In 2007, an open standard called "OpenSMILES" was developed by the Blue Obelisk open-source chemistry community.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Other 'linear' notations include the Wiswesser Line Notation (WLN), ROSDAL and SLN (Tripos Inc).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] In July 2006, the IUPAC introduced the InChI as a standard for formula representation.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] SMILES is generally considered to have the advantage of being more human-readable than InChI; it also has a wide base of software support with extensive theoretical backing (such as graph theory).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The term SMILES refers to a line notation for encoding molecular structures and specific instances should strictly be called SMILES strings.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] However, the term SMILES is also commonly used to refer to both a single SMILES string and a number of SMILES strings; the exact meaning is usually apparent from the context.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The terms "canonical" and "isomeric" can lead to some confusion when applied to SMILES.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The terms describe different attributes of SMILES strings and are not mutually exclusive.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Typically, a number of equally valid SMILES strings can be written for a molecule.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, `CCO`, `OCC` and `C(O)C` all specify the structure of ethanol.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Algorithms have been developed to generate the same SMILES string for a given molecule; of the many possible strings, these algorithms choose only one of them.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] This SMILES is unique for each structure, although dependent on the canonicalization algorithm used to generate it, and is termed the canonical SMILES.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] These algorithms first convert the SMILES to an internal representation of the molecular structure; an algorithm then examines that structure and produces a unique SMILES string.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Various algorithms for generating canonical SMILES have been developed and include those by Daylight Chemical Information Systems, OpenEye Scientific Software, MEDIT, Chemical Computing Group, MolSoft LLC, and the Chemistry Development Kit.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] A common application of canonical SMILES is indexing and ensuring uniqueness of molecules in a database.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] There is currently no systematic comparison across commercial software to test if such flaws exist in those packages.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] SMILES notation allows the specification of the configuration at tetrahedral centers and double bond geometry.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] These are structural features that cannot be specified by connectivity alone, and therefore the SMILES that encode this information is termed isomeric SMILES.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] A notable feature of these rules is that they allow rigorous partial specification of chirality.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The term isomeric SMILES is also applied to SMILES in which isomers are specified.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] In terms of a graph-based computational procedure, SMILES is a string obtained by printing the symbol nodes encountered in a depth-first tree traversal of a chemical graph.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The chemical graph is first trimmed to remove hydrogen atoms and cycles are broken to turn it into a spanning tree.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Where cycles have been broken, numeric suffix labels are included to indicate the connected nodes.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Parentheses are used to indicate points of branching on the tree.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] From the view point of a formal language theory, SMILES is a word.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] A SMILES is parsable with a context-free parser.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The use of this representation has been in the prediction of biochemical properties (incl. toxicity and biodegradability) based on the main principle of chemoinformatics that similar molecules have similar properties.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The predictive models implemented a syntactic pattern recognition approach (which involved defining a molecular distance) as well as a more robust scheme based on statistical pattern recognition.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Atoms are represented by the standard abbreviation of the chemical elements, in square brackets, such as `[Au]` for gold.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] All other elements must be enclosed in brackets, and have charges and hydrogens shown explicitly.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For instance, the SMILES for water may be written as either `O` or `[OH2]`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Hydrogen may also be written as a separate atom; water may also be written as `[H]O[H]`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] When brackets are used, the symbol `H` is added if the atom in brackets is bonded to one or more hydrogen, followed by the number of hydrogen atoms if greater than 1, then by the sign `+` for a positive charge or by `-` for a negative charge.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, `[NH4+]` for ammonium (NH+ 4).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] If there is more than one charge, it is normally written as digit; however, it is also possible to repeat the sign as many times as the ion has charges: one may write either `[Ti+4]` or `[Ti++++]` for titanium(IV) Ti4+.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Thus, the hydroxide anion ( OH−) is represented by `[OH-]`, the hydronium cation (H3O+) is `[OH3+]` and the cobalt(III) cation (Co3+) is either `[Co+3]` or `[Co+++]`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] A bond is represented using one of the symbols `. - = # $ : / \`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Bonds between aliphatic atoms are assumed to be single unless specified otherwise and are implied by adjacency in the SMILES string.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Although single bonds may be written as `-`, this is usually omitted.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, the SMILES for ethanol may be written as `C-C-O`, `CC-O` or `C-CO`, but is usually written `CCO`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Double, triple, and quadruple bonds are represented by the symbols `=`, `#`, and `$` respectively as illustrated by the SMILES `O=C=O` (carbon dioxide CO2), `C#N` (hydrogen cyanide HCN) and `[Ga+]$[As-]` (gallium arsenide).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] An additional type of bond is a "non-bond", indicated with `.`, to indicate that two parts are not bonded together.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, aqueous sodium chloride may be written as `[Na+].[Cl-]` to show the dissociation.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] An aromatic "one and a half" bond may be indicated with `:`; see § Aromaticity below.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Single bonds adjacent to double bonds may be represented using `/` or `\` to indicate stereochemical configuration; see § Stereochemistry below.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Ring structures are written by breaking each ring at an arbitrary point (although some choices will lead to a more legible SMILES than others) to make an acyclic structure and adding numerical ring closure labels to show connectivity between non-adjacent atoms.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, cyclohexane and (*p-*)dioxane may be written as `C1CCCCC1` and `O1CCOCC1` respectively.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, decalin (decahydronaphthalene) may be written as `C1CCCC2C1CCCC2`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] SMILES does not require that ring numbers be used in any particular order, and permits ring number zero, although this is rarely used.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Also, it is permitted to reuse ring numbers after the first ring has closed, although this usually makes formulae harder to read.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, bicyclohexyl is usually written as `C1CCCCC1C2CCCCC2`, but it may also be written as `C0CCCCC0C0CCCCC0`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Multiple digits after a single atom indicate multiple ring-closing bonds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, an alternative SMILES notation for decalin is `C1CCCC2CCCCC12`, where the final carbon participates in both ring-closing bonds 1 and 2.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] If two-digit ring numbers are required, the label is preceded by `%`, so `C%12` is a single ring-closing bond of ring 12.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Either or both of the digits may be preceded by a bond type to indicate the type of the ring-closing bond.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, cyclopropene is usually written `C1=CC1`, but if the double bond is chosen as the ring-closing bond, it may be written as `C=1CC1`, `C1CC=1`, or `C=1CC=1`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] (The first form is preferred.) `C=1CC-1` is illegal, as it explicitly specifies conflicting types for the ring-closing bond.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Ring-closing bonds may not be used to denote multiple bonds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, `C1C1` is not a valid alternative to `C=C` for ethylene.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] However, they may be used with non-bonds; `C1.C2.C12` is a peculiar but legal alternative way to write propane, more commonly written `CCC`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Choosing a ring-break point adjacent to attached groups can lead to a simpler SMILES form by avoiding branches.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, cyclohexane-1,2-diol is most simply written as `OC1CCCCC1O`; choosing a different ring-break location produces a branched structure that requires parentheses to write.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Using the aromatic bond symbol `:`, e.g.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Most commonly, by writing the constituent B, C, N, O, P and S atoms in lower-case forms `b`, `c`, `n`, `o`, `p` and `s`, respectively.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] In the latter case, bonds between two aromatic atoms are assumed (if not explicitly shown) to be aromatic bonds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Thus, benzene, pyridine and furan can be represented respectively by the SMILES `c1ccccc1`, `n1ccccc1` and `o1cccc1`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Aromatic nitrogen bonded to hydrogen, as found in pyrrole must be represented as `[nH]`; thus imidazole is written in SMILES notation as `n1c[nH]cc1`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] When aromatic atoms are singly bonded to each other, such as in biphenyl, a single bond must be shown explicitly: `c1ccccc1-c2ccccc2`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] This is one of the few cases where the single bond symbol `-` is required.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The Daylight and OpenEye algorithms for generating canonical SMILES differ in their treatment of aromaticity.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Branches are described with parentheses, as in `CCC(=O)O` for propionic acid and `FC(F)F` for fluoroform.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The first atom within the parentheses and the first atom after the parenthesized group are bonded to the same branch point atom.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The bond symbol must appear inside the parentheses; outside (e.g.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Substituted rings can be written with the branching point in the ring as illustrated by the SMILES `COc(c1)cccc1C#N` (see depiction) and `COc(cc1)ccc1C#N` (see depiction) which encode the 3 and 4-cyanoanisole isomers.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Writing SMILES for substituted rings in this way can make them more human-readable.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, bromochlorodifluoromethane may be written as `FC(Br)(Cl)F`, `BrC(F)(F)Cl`, `C(F)(Cl)(F)Br`, or the like.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Generally, a SMILES form is easiest to read if the simpler branch comes first, with the final, unparenthesized portion being the most complex.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The one form of branch which does *not* require parentheses is ring-closing bonds: the SMILES fragment `C1N` is equivalent to `C(1)N`, both denoting a bond between the `C` and the `N`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Choosing ring-closing bonds adjacent to branch points can reduce the number of parentheses required.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, toluene is normally written as `Cc1ccccc1` or `c1ccccc1C`, avoiding the parentheses required if written as `c1cc(C)ccc1` or `c1cc(ccc1)C`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] SMILES permits, but does not require, specification of stereoisomers.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Configuration around double bonds is specified using the characters `/` and `\` to show directional single bonds adjacent to a double bond.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Bond direction symbols always come in groups of at least two, of which the first is arbitrary.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] That is, `F\C=C\F` is the same as `F/C=C/F`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] When alternating single-double bonds are present, the groups are larger than two, with the middle directional symbols being adjacent to two double bonds.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, the common form of (2,4)-hexadiene is written `C/C=C/C=C/C`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] As a more complex example, beta-carotene has a very long backbone of alternating single and double bonds, which may be written `CC1CCC/C(C)=C1/C=C/C(C)=C/C=C/C(C)=C/C=C/C=C(C)/C=C/C=C(C)/C=C/C2=C(C)/CCCC2(C)C`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Configuration at tetrahedral carbon is specified by `@` or `@@`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Consider the four bonds in the order in which they appear, left to right, in the SMILES form.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Looking toward the central carbon from the perspective of the first bond, the other three are either clockwise or counter-clockwise.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] These cases are indicated with `@@` and `@`, respectively (because the `@` symbol itself is a counter-clockwise spiral).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, consider the amino acid alanine.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] One of its SMILES forms is `NC(C)C(=O)O`, more fully written as `N[CH](C)C(=O)O`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] L-Alanine, the more common enantiomer, is written as `N[C@@H](C)C(=O)O` (see depiction).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Looking from the nitrogen–carbon bond, the hydrogen (`H`), methyl (`C`), and carboxylate (`C(=O)O`) groups appear clockwise.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] D-Alanine can be written as `N[C@H](C)C(=O)O` (see depiction).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] While the order in which branches are specified in SMILES is normally unimportant, in this case it matters; swapping any two groups requires reversing the chirality indicator.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] If the branches are reversed so alanine is written as `NC(C(=O)O)C`, then the configuration also reverses; L-alanine is written as `N[C@H](C(=O)O)C` (see depiction).
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The SMILES specification includes elaborations on the `@` symbol to indicate stereochemistry around more complex chiral centers, such as trigonal bipyramidal molecular geometry.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Isotopes are specified with a number equal to the integer isotopic mass preceding the atomic symbol.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Benzene in which one atom is carbon-14 is written as `[14cH]1ccccc1` and deuterochloroform is `[2H]C(Cl)(Cl)Cl`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] `%` appears in front of the index of ring closure labels above 9; see § Rings above.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The SMILES notation is described extensively in the SMILES theory manual provided by Daylight Chemical Information Systems and a number of illustrative examples are presented.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Daylight's depict utility provides users with the means to check their own examples of SMILES and is a valuable educational tool.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The OpenSMILES specification also includes a large number of examples with commentary on their acceptance by different implementations.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] SMARTS is a line notation for specification of substructural patterns in molecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] While it uses many of the same symbols as SMILES, it also allows specification of wildcard atoms and bonds, which can be used to define substructural queries for chemical database searching.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] One common misconception is that SMARTS-based substructural searching involves matching of SMILES and SMARTS strings.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] In fact, both SMILES and SMARTS strings are first converted to internal graph representations which are searched for subgraph isomorphism.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] SMIRKS, a superset of "reaction SMILES" and a subset of "reaction SMARTS", is a line notation for specifying reaction transforms.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] The general syntax for the reaction extensions is `REACTANT>AGENT>PRODUCT` (without spaces), where any of the fields can either be left blank or filled with multiple molecules delineated with a dot (`.`), and other descriptions dependent on the base language.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Atoms can additionally be identified with a number (e.g.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] There are several computer tools for imputing atom-mapping information based on reaction SMILES.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] SMILES corresponds to discrete molecular structures.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] However many materials are macromolecules, which are too large (and often stochastic) to conveniently generate SMILES for.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] BigSMILES is an extension of SMILES that aims to provide an efficient representation system for macromolecules.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] It introduces a new curly bracket notation for listing polymer repeat units.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] For example, poly(ethylene-vinyl acetate) is written `{CC,CC(OC(=O)C)}`.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] SMILES can be converted back to two-dimensional representations using structure diagram generation (SDG) algorithms.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] Conversion to three-dimensional representation is achieved by energy-minimization approaches.
[src:cheminformatics-rdkit/simplified-molecular-input-line-entry-system] There are many downloadable and web-based conversion utilities.
